## 6. DTO Conventions

- Request DTO in `dto/request/`, Response DTO in `dto/response/`.
- Name: `{Entity}Request`, `{Entity}Response`.
- Use Java `record` for DTOs.
- Request DTOs include Jakarta validation annotations.

```java
// dto/request/RoomRequest.java
public record RoomRequest(
    @NotBlank String name,
    String description,
    GameModeEnum currentMode,
    Long duration
) {}

// dto/response/RoomResponse.java
public record RoomResponse(
    Long id,
    String name,
    String description,
    RoomStatusEnum status,
    GameModeEnum currentMode,
    Instant startTime,
    Long duration
) {}
```

---

## 7. Soft Delete

All entities extend `MetaData`, which provides the following audit fields:

| Field         | Type      | Description                        |
|---------------|-----------|------------------------------------|
| `createdDate` | `Instant` | Set automatically on create        |
| `createdBy`   | `String`  | Set automatically on create        |
| `updatedDate` | `Instant` | Set automatically on update        |
| `updatedBy`   | `String`  | Set automatically on update        |
| `isDeleted`   | `Boolean` | Soft-delete flag (default `false`) |
| `deletedDate` | `Instant` | Populated on soft delete           |
| `deletedBy`   | `String`  | Populated on soft delete           |

Rules:
- **Delete** = set `isDeleted = true` + populate `deletedDate` and `deletedBy`. Never call `repository.delete()` or `repository.deleteById()`.
- **All read queries** must filter `isDeleted = false`. No exceptions.

```java
@Transactional
public void delete(Long id) {
    Room room = roomRepository.findByIdAndIsDeletedFalse(id)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ResourceNotFoundException("Room not found: " + id));
    room.setIsDeleted(true);
    room.setDeletedDate(Instant.now());
    // deletedBy: set from SecurityContext if auth is available
    roomRepository.save(room);
}
```

